    "output": "To add subtitles from a .srt file to your video using FFmpeg, you can use the subtitles filter. This will burn the subtitles directly into the video stream (hardcoding), ensuring they are always visible regardless of the player.\n\nFor best compatibility, make sure both files are in the same folder or provide the full paths. Here, Iâ€™ll assume your video is input.mp4 and your subtitle file is subs.srt.\n\n- -vf \"subtitles=subs.srt\" applies the subtitles filter to burn them in.\n- -c:a copy copies the original audio stream without re-encoding.\n\n```bash\nffmpeg -i input.mp4 -vf \"subtitles=subs.srt\" -c:a copy output_with_subs.mp4\n```\n\nIf you want to keep the subtitles as a selectable soft subtitle track instead of burning them in, you can use:\n\n```bash\nffmpeg -i input.mp4 -i subs.srt -c copy -c:s mov_text output_with_subs.mp4\n```\n\n- -c:s mov_text adds the subtitle stream in a browser-compatible format (good for .mp4 files).\n- The subtitles will be selectable, not hardcoded.\n\nChoose the method that fits your use case. Let me know if you want support for a different container or more advanced subtitle styling!",
